Yes — evalite supports a `threshold` option per eval suite. You can set a minimum average score for each scorer, and the eval will fail (exit non-zero) if any scorer drops below it.

In your `evalite()` call, add a `threshold` property:

```ts
evalite<...>("Extraction Golden Cases", {
  data: ...,
  task: ...,
  scorers: [...],
  threshold: {
    "entity-precision": 0.7,
    "entity-recall": 0.7,
    "category-accuracy": 0.6,
    // any scorer name → minimum average score across all cases
  },
});
```

When any scorer's average falls below its threshold, evalite exits with a non-zero code — so `bun run eval` fails in CI just like a test.

For the observer eval, same pattern:

```ts
evalite<...>("Observer LLM Reasoning Quality", {
  ...
  threshold: {
    "verdict-accuracy": 0.8,
    "confidence-calibration": 0.7,
    "reasoning-quality": 0.7,
    "no-hallucination": 1.0,
    "factuality": 0.8,
  },
});
```

Want me to add thresholds to your eval files? If so, what minimum scores do you want to enforce (or should I pick reasonable defaults based on current performance)?
